    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="160"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d160">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–1454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-14">May 14,
                            1954</date>.<note n="1" xml:id="d160fn1">The file copy indicates no
                            time, of transmittal. It was, however, received in Washington at 7:28
                            p.m. on May 14.</note>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>78. Repeated information Department <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 211,
                    Tokyo 61. Tokyo pass <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss>. Re <gloss
                        target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 196,<note n="2" xml:id="d160fn2">Dated May
                        13, <ref target="#pg_261">p. 261</ref>.</note> 200.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d160fn3">Same as telegram 74, May 13, from Geneva, <ref
                            target="#pg_264">p. 264</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>After plenary session May 13 <persName corresp="#p_YKT1">Young</persName>
                            discussed draft basic proposal with <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                                >Pyun</persName> and <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> delegation.
                            As they were disturbed and even angry over <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                                >Eden</persName>’s five points and especially his fourth point
                                (<gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 203<note n="4"
                                xml:id="d160fn4">Dated May 13, <ref target="#pg_262">p.
                                262</ref>.</note>), their initial reaction was critical: <list>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                                <item>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> and other delegates
                                    objected to phrase “throughout Korea” in first paragraph draft.
                                    He said scope of elections should be left unspecified in basic
                                    principles. He repeated <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                                    would agree to general elections in Korea if Chinese Communists
                                    withdrew completely from Korea prior such elections;</item>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                                <item>
                                    <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> delegation strongly
                                    preferred specific reference to <gloss target="#t_UNCURK1"
                                        >UNCURK</gloss> instead of to United Nations Commission.
                                    Their insistence on this point reflected their deep concern over
                                    the vagueness <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>’s
                                    proposal for a commission composed of a “panel acceptable to
                                    Geneva conference”. <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                                    delegation interprets <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                                    >Eden</persName>’s phraseology possibly include neutrals such as
                                    India and Communists United Nations members such as
                                    Czechoslovakia and Poland. <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                                        >Pyun</persName> and <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                                    delegates said any such commission totally unacceptable.
                                        <persName corresp="#p_YKT1">Young</persName> referred to
                                        <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s objections to
                                        <gloss target="#t_UNCURK1">UNCURK</gloss> as reported by
                                        <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> and <persName
                                        corresp="#p_DAH1">Dean</persName>. <persName
                                        corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> said he would persuade
                                    President insist on <gloss target="#t_UNCURK1">UNCURK</gloss>
                                    since its composition satisfactory.</item>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">c</hi>)</label>
                                <item>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> considered any
                                    reference to question withdrawal non-Korean forces, even such
                                    vague wording as paragraph 5 draft proposal, should be omitted.
                                        <persName corresp="#p_YKT1">Young</persName> pointed out
                                    impracticability no reference this matter.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> delegation reacted negatively to
                            draft proposal in contrast to affirmative reaction draft of plan B.
                            Their initial criticism explained <pb facs="0297" n="271"
                                xml:id="pg_271"/> largely by concern over <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                                >Eden</persName>’s remarks and also Philippine proposal for
                            constitutional convention repeated again in meeting of 16 May 13.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Following meeting of working group of 9 on May 14 <persName
                            corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> told us again present position <gloss
                            target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> Government is general elections must be
                        conditioned on prior total withdrawal Chinese Communist forces.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName>Oliver</persName> told <persName corresp="#p_YKT1"
                            >Young</persName> May 14: <list>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Several days ago <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> sent
                                telegram <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> suggesting
                                    <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> public statement Seoul and
                                Geneva that <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> not opposing general
                                elections but insisting on prior total Chinese Communist withdrawal.
                                Purpose to offset impression in United States press <gloss
                                    target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> preventing agreement among allies
                                by opposing generalizations. <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                                    >Pyun</persName> replied such statement inadvisable because it
                                would create confusion in Geneva and force division among allies;
                                and</item>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                            <item>He and <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> delegation have
                                discussed proposal for withdrawal bulk but not all foreign forces
                                from Korea prior to elections and he thinks <persName
                                    corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> might be persuaded accept this
                                along with fundamental principles on United Nations supervision and
                                genuinely free elections. Said he would try draft telegram to
                                    <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> on such lines.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
